const GLOSSARY_CISA = [
  { term:"Access Control", definition:"Mechanisms that restrict access to systems and data to authorized users based on defined permissions. Auditors verify that access is granted on least-privilege and need-to-know principles." },
  { term:"Audit Charter", definition:"A formal document that defines the internal audit function's purpose, authority, and responsibility within the organization. The audit charter is approved by the board or audit committee and establishes the auditor's independence and scope." },
  { term:"Audit Documentation", definition:"The working papers and records that support the audit work performed, evidence gathered, and conclusions reached. Adequate documentation enables review and demonstrates that the audit was conducted per standards." },
  { term:"Audit Evidence", definition:"Information collected by auditors to support audit conclusions. Evidence must be sufficient (enough to support conclusions), reliable (from trusted sources), relevant (related to objectives), and useful (assists in meeting audit goals)." },
  { term:"Audit Objective", definition:"The specific goal or purpose that an audit engagement seeks to achieve, such as verifying control effectiveness or compliance. Objectives guide the scope and procedures of the audit." },
  { term:"Audit Planning", definition:"The process of determining the objectives, scope, timing, and resource requirements for an audit engagement. Effective planning ensures audits are focused, efficient, and aligned with organizational risk priorities." },
  { term:"Audit Risk", definition:"The risk that an auditor may issue an incorrect opinion due to material misstatements not being detected. Audit risk has three components: inherent risk, control risk, and detection risk." },
  { term:"Audit Scope", definition:"The boundary of an audit engagement, defining the systems, processes, locations, and time period to be examined. A clearly defined scope ensures resources focus on relevant areas." },
  { term:"Audit Universe", definition:"The complete population of auditable entities within an organization, including processes, systems, and departments. The audit universe is used to develop the audit plan and prioritize engagements based on risk." },
  { term:"Availability", definition:"The property of information and systems being accessible and usable upon demand by authorized entities. Availability is one of the three core principles of information security (CIA triad) and is critical for business operations." },
  { term:"Backup Strategy", definition:"A defined approach for copying and retaining data to enable recovery after loss or corruption. It specifies backup types, frequency, retention, and offsite storage aligned with RPO requirements." },
  { term:"Baseline", definition:"A formally reviewed and agreed reference point for requirements, configuration, or performance that changes are measured against. It provides a stable basis for controlling scope and change." },
  { term:"Business Continuity Plan (BCP)", definition:"A documented set of procedures enabling an organization to continue critical operations during and after a disruption. Auditors evaluate its completeness, currency, and testing adequacy." },
  { term:"Business Impact Analysis (BIA)", definition:"A process that identifies critical business functions and quantifies the impact of their disruption over time. It establishes recovery priorities, RTOs, and RPOs used in continuity planning." },
  { term:"Capacity Management", definition:"The process of ensuring that IT resources are sufficient to meet current and future business demand cost-effectively. It involves monitoring, analysis, and planning of system performance and utilization." },
  { term:"Change Management", definition:"A formal process for requesting, evaluating, approving, implementing, and reviewing changes to IT systems and infrastructure. Effective change management prevents unauthorized modifications and reduces the risk of outages or security breaches." },
  { term:"COBIT", definition:"Control Objectives for Information and Related Technologies — a governance and management framework for enterprise IT published by ISACA. COBIT provides principles, practices, and tools to manage and govern IT across the enterprise." },
  { term:"Compliance", definition:"Adherence to applicable laws, regulations, standards, and organizational policies. IS auditors assess compliance to ensure the organization meets its legal and regulatory obligations and internal control requirements." },
  { term:"Compliance Testing", definition:"Audit procedures that verify whether controls are operating as designed and whether policies and procedures are being followed. It provides assurance that controls are present and functioning." },
  { term:"Computer-Assisted Audit Technique (CAAT)", definition:"Software tools and techniques used by auditors to analyze large volumes of data, test controls, and perform substantive procedures electronically. Examples include generalized audit software and test data." },
  { term:"Confidentiality", definition:"The property of information being accessible only to those authorized to have access. Confidentiality is one of the three core principles of the CIA triad and is protected through access controls, encryption, and classification policies." },
  { term:"Continuous Auditing", definition:"An approach that uses automated tools to collect audit evidence and indicators on a real-time or near-real-time basis. It enables timely detection of anomalies and control breakdowns." },
  { term:"Control", definition:"Any policy, procedure, practice, or organizational structure designed to provide reasonable assurance that business objectives will be achieved and undesired events will be prevented or detected and corrected." },
  { term:"Control Environment", definition:"The overall culture, awareness, and actions of management and employees regarding the importance of controls. The control environment forms the foundation for all other internal control components." },
  { term:"Control Risk", definition:"The risk that a material misstatement or weakness would not be prevented or detected and corrected on a timely basis by an entity's internal controls. High control risk indicates weak internal controls." },
  { term:"Control Self-Assessment (CSA)", definition:"A methodology in which business process owners assess the adequacy of their own controls, often facilitated by auditors. It increases ownership of controls and complements traditional auditing." },
  { term:"Corrective Control", definition:"A control designed to remedy problems discovered by detective controls and restore normal operations. Examples include backups, incident response procedures, and error correction routines." },
  { term:"Data Classification", definition:"The process of categorizing information by sensitivity and criticality to apply appropriate protection levels. It guides handling, access, retention, and disposal controls throughout the data lifecycle." },
  { term:"Data Integrity", definition:"The property that data has not been modified in an unauthorized or undetected manner. Data integrity ensures that information is accurate, complete, and has not been altered during storage, processing, or transmission." },
  { term:"Data Migration", definition:"The process of transferring data from a legacy system to a new system during implementation. Auditors verify completeness, accuracy, and integrity of data through reconciliation and validation controls." },
  { term:"Detection Risk", definition:"The risk that the auditor's own procedures will fail to detect an existing material error or weakness. It is influenced by the nature, timing, and extent of testing performed." },
  { term:"Detective Control", definition:"A control designed to discover and report errors or irregularities that have already occurred. Examples include audit logs, exception reports, and periodic reconciliations." },
  { term:"Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)", definition:"A documented process or set of procedures to recover and protect IT infrastructure in the event of a disaster. The DRP defines roles, communication procedures, recovery priorities, and steps to restore operations." },
  { term:"Encryption", definition:"The process of transforming readable data into ciphertext to protect its confidentiality during storage or transmission. Auditors assess key management and algorithm strength to evaluate its effectiveness." },
  { term:"Enterprise Architecture", definition:"A structured description of an organization's business processes, information, applications, and technology and their interrelationships. It provides a blueprint that guides IT decisions and standardization." },
  { term:"Feasibility Study", definition:"An early SDLC analysis that evaluates whether a proposed system is technically, economically, and operationally viable. It informs the go or no-go decision before significant investment." },
  { term:"Follow-Up Audit", definition:"Procedures performed to determine whether management has implemented agreed corrective actions for previously reported findings. It confirms that identified risks have been adequately remediated." },
  { term:"Function Point Analysis", definition:"A technique for measuring the size and complexity of software based on its functionality delivered to users. It supports estimation of development effort and cost independent of technology." },
  { term:"Generalized Audit Software (GAS)", definition:"A category of CAAT tools that read, process, and analyze data from various file formats independent of the source application. It supports functions like sampling, recalculation, and duplicate detection." },
  { term:"Identity and Access Management (IAM)", definition:"The framework of policies and technologies for managing digital identities and controlling user access to resources. It covers provisioning, authentication, authorization, and de-provisioning." },
  { term:"Incident Management", definition:"The process of detecting, responding to, and resolving events that disrupt or reduce the quality of IT services. It aims to restore normal service operation as quickly as possible." },
  { term:"Inherent Risk", definition:"The level of risk that exists before any controls are applied. Inherent risk reflects the natural exposure of a process or system based on its nature, complexity, and the threats it faces." },
  { term:"Internal Audit", definition:"An independent appraisal function established within an organization to examine and evaluate its activities as a service to the organization. Internal audit helps management improve governance, risk management, and controls." },
  { term:"ISACA", definition:"Information Systems Audit and Control Association — a global organization that provides guidance, standards, and certifications for IS audit, governance, risk, and security professionals including the CISA, CISM, and CRISC." },
  { term:"IS Audit", definition:"The process of collecting and evaluating evidence to determine whether an information system safeguards assets, maintains data integrity, achieves organizational goals effectively, and consumes resources efficiently." },
  { term:"IS Auditor", definition:"A professional who objectively evaluates information systems, controls, and operations to provide assurance that IT risks are managed and controls are operating effectively. IS auditors follow professional standards issued by ISACA." },
  { term:"IT General Controls (ITGC)", definition:"Broad controls that apply to all IT systems and components throughout an organization. ITGCs include access controls, change management, data backup, and operations controls that support application-level controls." },
  { term:"IT Governance", definition:"The framework of leadership, structures, and processes that ensure IT supports and extends the organization's strategies and objectives. IT governance addresses accountability, decision-making, and performance measurement for IT." },
  { term:"ITIL", definition:"Information Technology Infrastructure Library — a framework of best practices for IT service management. ITIL provides guidance on service strategy, design, transition, operation, and continual service improvement." },
  { term:"IT Portfolio Management", definition:"The process of managing IT investments and projects as a collective portfolio to optimize value and balance risk. It supports prioritization of initiatives against strategic objectives and resource constraints." },
  { term:"IT Steering Committee", definition:"A management-level group that oversees IT projects, prioritizes initiatives, and allocates resources at the operational level. It ensures IT activities align with approved strategy and budgets." },
  { term:"IT Strategy Committee", definition:"A board-level body that advises on strategic IT direction, investment, and alignment with enterprise objectives. It provides governance oversight of major IT decisions and priorities." },
  { term:"Job Scheduling", definition:"The automated management of batch processing and routine IT tasks according to defined sequences and timing. Auditors review scheduling controls to ensure completeness, accuracy, and error handling." },
  { term:"Judgmental Sampling", definition:"A non-statistical sampling approach where the auditor selects items based on experience, knowledge, and professional judgment rather than random probability. Results cannot be statistically projected to the population." },
  { term:"Key Performance Indicator (KPI)", definition:"A measurable value that demonstrates how effectively an organization or process is achieving key business objectives. KPIs provide management with actionable data for decision-making and performance improvement." },
  { term:"Key Risk Indicator (KRI)", definition:"A metric used to provide an early signal of increasing risk exposure in a process or area. Monitoring KRIs helps management and auditors anticipate control breakdowns before they materialize." },
  { term:"Least Privilege", definition:"The security principle that users, processes, and systems should be granted only the minimum permissions necessary to perform their functions. Least privilege reduces the attack surface and limits the potential damage from compromised accounts." },
  { term:"Management Letter", definition:"A communication from auditors to management that identifies internal control weaknesses, inefficiencies, or other observations noted during an audit but not included in the formal audit report." },
  { term:"Materiality", definition:"The significance of an error, omission, or weakness that would cause reasonable users to make different decisions if they were aware of it. Auditors focus audit procedures on material items that could substantially affect conclusions." },
  { term:"Outsourcing", definition:"The practice of contracting IT functions or services to an external third-party provider. Auditors evaluate contract terms, service levels, and vendor controls to manage associated risks." },
  { term:"Penetration Testing", definition:"A simulated cyberattack conducted to evaluate the security of a system by attempting to exploit vulnerabilities. Penetration testing provides evidence of exploitable vulnerabilities and validates the effectiveness of security controls." },
  { term:"Physical Access Control", definition:"Measures that restrict entry to facilities, equipment, and sensitive areas to authorized individuals. Examples include badge readers, biometric locks, mantraps, and security guards." },
  { term:"Post-Implementation Review", definition:"An evaluation conducted after a system is deployed to assess whether it delivered expected benefits and met objectives. It identifies lessons learned and any residual issues requiring correction." },
  { term:"Preventive Control", definition:"A control designed to deter problems before they occur. Examples include access controls, encryption, input validation, and separation of duties that prevent unauthorized actions or errors from being introduced." },
  { term:"Problem Management", definition:"The process of identifying and eliminating the root causes of recurring incidents to prevent future disruptions. It focuses on permanent resolution rather than temporary restoration." },
  { term:"Project Management", definition:"The discipline of planning, executing, and controlling projects to meet objectives within scope, time, and budget. Auditors review project governance, milestones, and controls to assess delivery risk." },
  { term:"Recovery Point Objective (RPO)", definition:"The maximum tolerable period of data loss measured in time. RPO defines how much data an organization can afford to lose and drives decisions about backup frequency and data replication strategies." },
  { term:"Recovery Time Objective (RTO)", definition:"The maximum acceptable time to restore a system or process following a disruption. RTO drives disaster recovery planning and investment decisions to ensure operations resume within the defined window." },
  { term:"Regression Testing", definition:"Testing that re-verifies existing functionality after changes to ensure new modifications have not introduced defects. It confirms that unchanged features continue to operate correctly." },
  { term:"Risk Assessment", definition:"A process to identify threats and vulnerabilities applicable to an organization's IT environment, assess the likelihood and impact of those risks, and prioritize actions to address them." },
  { term:"Risk-Based Audit Planning", definition:"An approach that directs audit resources toward the areas of greatest risk to the organization. Auditors assess inherent and control risk to prioritize engagements and determine the nature, timing, and extent of testing." },
  { term:"Sampling", definition:"The practice of selecting a subset of a population for testing. In IS auditing, sampling is used when it is impractical to test all items. Samples must be representative, and results are projected to the full population." },
  { term:"Segregation of Duties", definition:"A control principle that divides critical tasks among different individuals so that no single person controls a transaction end to end. It reduces the risk of error, fraud, and unauthorized activity." },
  { term:"Segregation of Duties (SOD)", definition:"A control that divides critical tasks among multiple individuals to prevent any single person from having complete control over a process. SOD reduces the risk of fraud, errors, and unauthorized activities." },
  { term:"Service Level Agreement (SLA)", definition:"A contract between a service provider and customer that defines the expected level of service, including availability, performance targets, and remedies for non-compliance." },
  { term:"SOC Report", definition:"A Service Organization Control report produced by an independent auditor that provides assurance about the controls of a service organization. SOC 1 covers financial reporting controls; SOC 2 covers security, availability, and privacy." },
  { term:"Statistical Sampling", definition:"A sampling method using probability theory to select items so that results can be objectively projected to the entire population. It allows quantification of sampling risk and confidence levels." },
  { term:"Substantive Testing", definition:"Audit procedures performed to detect material misstatements or irregularities in financial statements or systems. Substantive tests provide direct evidence about the accuracy and completeness of data and transactions." },
  { term:"Systems Development Life Cycle (SDLC)", definition:"A structured framework of phases for developing information systems, from feasibility through maintenance. Auditors assess whether controls and approvals exist at each phase to ensure quality and compliance." },
  { term:"Test of Controls", definition:"Audit procedures designed to evaluate the operating effectiveness of controls in preventing or detecting material misstatements. Tests of controls determine whether controls are functioning as designed during the audit period." },
  { term:"Two-Factor Authentication", definition:"An access control method requiring two distinct forms of identity verification from separate categories such as knowledge and possession. It strengthens authentication beyond a single password." },
  { term:"User Acceptance Testing (UAT)", definition:"Testing performed by end users to confirm that a system meets business requirements before going live. Successful UAT provides assurance that the system functions as intended in real conditions." },
  { term:"Vulnerability", definition:"A weakness in an information system, security procedure, internal control, or implementation that could be exploited by a threat agent. Identified vulnerabilities should be assessed for risk and remediated or mitigated." },
  { term:"Working Papers", definition:"Documentation prepared by auditors during an engagement that records the audit procedures performed, evidence obtained, and conclusions reached. Working papers support the audit report and demonstrate professional due care." },
  { term:"ITAF (IT Assurance Framework)", definition:"ISACA's professional practices framework that provides guidance, standards, and tools for IS audit and assurance engagements. Auditors use ITAF's mandatory standards, guidelines, and techniques to plan, execute, and report assurance work consistently." },
  { term:"Attribute Sampling", definition:"A statistical sampling method used to estimate the rate of occurrence of a specific control condition (present/absent) in a population. Auditors apply it in compliance testing to conclude whether a control's deviation rate is within an acceptable tolerable limit." },
  { term:"Variable Sampling", definition:"A statistical sampling technique that estimates a numerical value such as a monetary balance rather than a rate of occurrence. It is used primarily in substantive testing to project the dollar value of misstatement in an account population." },
  { term:"Stop-or-Go Sampling", definition:"A sequential sampling approach that lets the auditor stop testing as soon as sufficient evidence supports a conclusion, minimizing sample size when few errors are expected. It reduces audit effort while still controlling sampling risk." },
  { term:"Discovery Sampling", definition:"A form of attribute sampling designed to detect at least one instance of a critical condition, such as fraud or a serious irregularity, when its occurrence rate is very low. Finding even a single exception typically triggers expanded investigation." },
  { term:"Statistical vs Judgmental Sampling", definition:"Statistical sampling uses probability theory and random selection so results can be objectively projected with measurable sampling risk. Judgmental (non-statistical) sampling relies on the auditor's experience to select items, offering flexibility but no quantifiable confidence level." },
  { term:"Stratified Sampling", definition:"A technique that divides a population into homogeneous subgroups (strata) before sampling to reduce variance and improve efficiency. Auditors often stratify by monetary value so high-value items receive greater testing emphasis." },
  { term:"Tolerable Error Rate", definition:"The maximum deviation or misstatement rate an auditor is willing to accept while still concluding that a control or balance is acceptable. It is set during planning and compared against the sample's projected error rate." },
  { term:"Sampling Risk", definition:"The risk that the auditor's conclusion based on a sample differs from the conclusion that would result from testing the entire population. It includes the risk of incorrect acceptance and the risk of incorrect rejection." },
  { term:"Nonsampling Risk", definition:"The portion of audit risk not related to sample size, arising from human error such as misapplying procedures, misinterpreting evidence, or overlooking exceptions. It cannot be reduced by increasing the sample but only through supervision, training, and quality review." },
  { term:"Coefficient of Determination", definition:"A statistical measure (R-squared) indicating how much of the variation in one variable is explained by another in regression analysis. Auditors use it in analytical procedures to assess the strength of relationships used for expectation modeling." },
  { term:"Integrated Test Facility (ITF)", definition:"A continuous audit technique that creates a fictitious entity within the live production system and processes test transactions against it alongside real data. It lets auditors verify processing accuracy without disrupting genuine records, provided test data is later reversed out." },
  { term:"Test Data Method", definition:"An audit technique in which the auditor submits a set of prepared transactions, including valid and invalid cases, through the application to verify that programmed controls behave as expected. Results are compared to predetermined outcomes to confirm control effectiveness." },
  { term:"Parallel Simulation", definition:"An audit technique in which the auditor reprocesses actual production data using an independently controlled program that replicates the application's logic. Discrepancies between the simulation's output and the real system's output indicate potential processing or control weaknesses." },
  { term:"Embedded Audit Module", definition:"Program code built into an application that continuously captures or flags transactions meeting audit-defined criteria for later review. It supports continuous auditing but requires auditor involvement during system development to be implemented." },
  { term:"SCARF (Systems Control Audit Review File)", definition:"A continuous auditing technique that embeds audit routines in the application to collect exceptional or policy-violating transactions into a special file for auditor examination. It enables ongoing monitoring of complex, high-volume systems." },
  { term:"Snapshot Technique", definition:"A continuous audit method that captures the state of data and processing at selected points as a transaction moves through an application. The captured images let the auditor trace and verify how the system transformed the transaction." },
  { term:"Audit Hook", definition:"Embedded exit points in application code that flag or route transactions meeting predefined conditions for auditor attention. Hooks act as an early-warning mechanism, alerting auditors to suspicious activity before a full irregularity develops." },
  { term:"Continuous vs Concurrent Auditing", definition:"Continuous auditing produces audit results simultaneously with or shortly after events occur through automated collection and analysis. Concurrent auditing embeds audit procedures directly into the application's processing so evidence is gathered as transactions execute." },
  { term:"Reasonableness Check", definition:"An input or processing control that validates data against expected logical limits or relationships, such as hours worked not exceeding a plausible maximum. It detects values that are individually valid in format but implausible in context." },
  { term:"Check Digit", definition:"A calculated digit appended to an identifier that validates the integrity of the preceding digits using a mathematical algorithm. Auditors verify it to confirm that transposition or transcription errors in key fields are detected at input." },
  { term:"Hash Total", definition:"A control total computed from a data field that has no intrinsic arithmetic meaning, such as summed account numbers, used solely to detect data loss or alteration. Matching the recomputed hash confirms completeness of processing." },
  { term:"Batch Control Total", definition:"A total accumulated for a batch of transactions before processing and compared to a total generated after processing to ensure completeness and accuracy. Discrepancies indicate missing, duplicated, or altered records." },
  { term:"Run-to-Run Total", definition:"A processing control that carries forward and reconciles control totals between successive stages of a multi-step processing cycle. It ensures that no data is lost or improperly added as information passes from one program run to the next." },
  { term:"Limit Check", definition:"An input validation control that verifies a data value falls within a predefined upper or lower boundary. Unlike a range check with two bounds, a limit check typically enforces a single threshold to catch out-of-bounds entries." },
  { term:"Completeness Check", definition:"An edit control that confirms all required data fields in a record contain values before the transaction is accepted for processing. It prevents incomplete records that could cause downstream processing errors." },
  { term:"Existence Check", definition:"A validation control that verifies entered data corresponds to a valid, authorized value in a master or reference file, such as a valid customer or product code. It prevents processing of transactions referencing nonexistent entities." },
  { term:"Referential Integrity", definition:"A database control ensuring that a foreign key value always references an existing, valid primary key in a related table. Auditors test it to confirm that relationships between tables cannot be broken by orphaned or dangling records." },
  { term:"Concurrency Control", definition:"Database mechanisms such as locking and timestamping that manage simultaneous access so that concurrent transactions do not corrupt data or produce inconsistent results. It preserves isolation and integrity in multi-user environments." },
  { term:"Two-Phase Commit", definition:"A distributed transaction protocol that coordinates multiple databases to either all commit or all roll back a transaction, preserving consistency. The prepare phase confirms readiness and the commit phase finalizes, preventing partial updates across systems." },
  { term:"ACID Properties", definition:"The four guarantees of reliable database transactions: Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability. Auditors rely on these properties to conclude that a database maintains data integrity even during failures or concurrent access." },
  { term:"Normalization", definition:"The process of organizing relational database tables to reduce redundancy and dependency, typically through successive normal forms. It improves data integrity but auditors weigh it against denormalization used for performance in reporting systems." },
  { term:"Database Views", definition:"Virtual tables defined by stored queries that present a controlled subset of underlying data to users. Auditors evaluate views as an access control that enforces least privilege by restricting the columns and rows a user can see." },
  { term:"Object-Oriented vs Relational DB", definition:"Relational databases store data in tables of rows and columns linked by keys, while object-oriented databases store data as objects encapsulating attributes and behavior. The choice affects how integrity, access, and complex data relationships are controlled and audited." },
  { term:"Data Warehouse vs Data Mart", definition:"A data warehouse is a large, enterprise-wide repository of integrated historical data for analysis, while a data mart is a smaller subset focused on a specific business function or department. Auditors assess data quality, access controls, and ETL integrity for both." },
  { term:"ETL (Extract, Transform, Load)", definition:"The process of extracting data from source systems, transforming it to a consistent format, and loading it into a target repository such as a data warehouse. Auditors verify transformation logic and reconciliation controls to ensure completeness and accuracy of loaded data." },
  { term:"COBIT Process Reference Model", definition:"COBIT's structured catalog of governance and management objectives grouped into domains that map enterprise IT activities to stakeholder needs. Auditors use it as a benchmark to assess IT governance maturity and control coverage." },
  { term:"RACI Chart", definition:"A responsibility assignment matrix identifying who is Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, and Informed for each task or deliverable. Auditors use it to evaluate clarity of roles and to confirm that accountability is properly assigned and segregated." },
  { term:"Capability Maturity Model (CMM)", definition:"A framework describing the evolution of a process through defined maturity levels from initial/ad hoc to optimized. Auditors use maturity ratings to benchmark the state of IT processes and to recommend improvement paths." },
  { term:"Critical Path Method (CPM)", definition:"A project scheduling technique that identifies the longest sequence of dependent tasks determining the minimum project duration. Auditors review the critical path to evaluate whether schedule risks and dependencies are properly managed." },
  { term:"PERT (Program Evaluation Review Technique)", definition:"A project management technique that estimates task duration using optimistic, most likely, and pessimistic times to account for uncertainty. It helps auditors assess the realism of schedules for projects with unpredictable activities." },
  { term:"Gantt Chart", definition:"A bar chart that displays project tasks against a timeline, showing start and end dates, durations, and overlaps. Auditors use it to assess whether project progress is tracked and milestones are being met." },
  { term:"Earned Value Analysis", definition:"A project control technique that integrates scope, schedule, and cost to measure performance against the plan using metrics like cost and schedule variance. Auditors rely on it to independently assess whether a project is on budget and on schedule." },
  { term:"SDLC Phases", definition:"The structured stages of the systems development life cycle, typically feasibility, requirements, design, development, testing, implementation, and post-implementation review. Auditors evaluate control activities and approvals at each phase and prefer involvement early to influence controls." },
  { term:"Agile/Scrum/Kanban", definition:"Iterative development approaches that deliver software incrementally; Scrum uses time-boxed sprints and defined roles while Kanban emphasizes continuous flow and work-in-progress limits. Auditors adapt control testing to iterative artifacts such as backlogs, sprint reviews, and definitions of done." },
  { term:"DevOps", definition:"A practice integrating development and operations with automation to enable frequent, reliable software releases through continuous integration and delivery pipelines. Auditors assess automated testing, approval gates, and segregation controls within the pipeline." },
  { term:"Regression vs Sanity Testing", definition:"Regression testing re-runs existing test cases to confirm that new changes have not broken previously working functionality, while sanity testing is a narrow, quick check that specific fixed functionality works. Auditors confirm regression testing occurs before changes reach production." },
  { term:"White-box vs Black-box Testing", definition:"White-box testing examines internal code logic and paths with knowledge of the program's structure, while black-box testing validates inputs and outputs against requirements without knowledge of internals. A balanced test strategy uses both to give auditors assurance over functionality and logic." },
  { term:"Parallel vs Phased vs Pilot vs Big-Bang Changeover", definition:"Conversion strategies for moving to a new system: parallel runs old and new together, phased migrates in stages, pilot deploys to a limited group first, and big-bang switches everything at once. Parallel and phased are lower risk while big-bang is fastest but riskiest." },
  { term:"Fallback Procedures", definition:"Predefined steps to revert to the prior system or state if a conversion or change fails. Auditors confirm that documented, tested fallback plans exist so operations can recover from a failed implementation." },
  { term:"Software Escrow", definition:"An arrangement where a third party holds source code and documentation, releasing it to the licensee if the vendor fails or ceases support. Auditors verify escrow agreements to ensure continued maintainability of critical vendor software." },
  { term:"Electronic Vaulting", definition:"The batch transfer of backup data to an offsite storage facility electronically rather than by physical media transport. It shortens recovery timeframes and reduces the risk of data loss between backups." },
  { term:"Remote Journaling", definition:"The real-time or near-real-time transmission of database transaction logs (journals) to an offsite location. It enables recovery to a point close to failure by replaying captured transactions, supporting a low recovery point objective." },
  { term:"Mirroring", definition:"The technique of maintaining an exact real-time duplicate of data or systems at a separate location. Disk or site mirroring provides near-zero data loss and rapid recovery but at higher cost and bandwidth demand." },
  { term:"RAID Levels", definition:"Redundant Array of Independent Disks configurations that combine drives for performance and fault tolerance; levels differ in striping, mirroring, and parity such as RAID 1 mirroring and RAID 5 striping with parity. Auditors assess whether the chosen level meets availability and recovery requirements." },
  { term:"Clustering", definition:"Grouping multiple servers so they operate as a single logical system, allowing workload sharing and automatic failover if a node fails. Auditors evaluate clustering as a high-availability control supporting continuity objectives." },
  { term:"Load Balancing", definition:"Distributing incoming workload across multiple servers or resources to optimize performance, throughput, and availability. It also contributes to resilience by preventing any single node from becoming a failure point." },
  { term:"Reciprocal Agreement", definition:"A mutual arrangement between two organizations to provide processing support to each other in the event of a disaster. It is low cost but often impractical due to capacity, compatibility, and confidentiality concerns, and is difficult to enforce." },
  { term:"Mobile Site", definition:"A transportable, self-contained recovery facility such as a trailer equipped with computing infrastructure that can be delivered to a needed location. It provides flexible recovery capacity when a fixed alternate site is unavailable." },
  { term:"Warm/Hot/Cold Site", definition:"Alternate processing facilities that differ in readiness: a hot site is fully equipped and can operate almost immediately, a warm site has partial infrastructure requiring setup, and a cold site provides only basic space and utilities. Auditors match the site type to the organization's recovery time objective." },
  { term:"MTD/RTO/RPO/SDO/MTO", definition:"Key recovery metrics: Maximum Tolerable Downtime is the longest outage the business can survive, Recovery Time Objective is the target to restore service, Recovery Point Objective is the acceptable data loss window, Service Delivery Objective is the reduced service level during recovery, and Maximum Tolerable Outage is the time an organization can operate in that reduced mode." },
  { term:"Business Continuity vs Disaster Recovery", definition:"Business continuity is the broad strategy for keeping the whole organization operating during and after a disruption, while disaster recovery focuses specifically on restoring IT systems and data. Auditors confirm that DR plans align with and support the wider BCP." },
  { term:"Incident vs Problem Management", definition:"Incident management restores normal service as quickly as possible after a disruption, while problem management identifies and eliminates the underlying root cause to prevent recurrence. Auditors verify both processes exist and that recurring incidents feed into problem analysis." },
  { term:"Configuration Management Database (CMDB)", definition:"A repository that records information about IT configuration items and their relationships across the environment. Auditors use it to verify that assets are tracked, changes are controlled, and dependencies are understood for impact analysis." },
  { term:"Release Management", definition:"The process of planning, building, testing, and deploying changes into production as controlled releases. Auditors evaluate it to confirm that only authorized, tested, and approved releases reach the live environment." },
  { term:"Segregation of Duties Matrix", definition:"A grid mapping job functions against one another to identify incompatible duty combinations that could enable error or fraud. Auditors use it to detect conflicts such as one person both initiating and approving transactions." },
  { term:"Compensating Control for SoD", definition:"An alternative control implemented when full segregation of duties is impractical, such as in small organizations. Examples include supervisory review, transaction logging, and reconciliation, which mitigate the risk of an individual performing incompatible functions." },
  { term:"Data Owner vs Custodian", definition:"The data owner is the business role accountable for classifying information and authorizing access, while the custodian is responsible for implementing and maintaining protective controls, typically in IT. Auditors confirm this separation to ensure accountability and proper control implementation." },
  { term:"Encryption Key Escrow", definition:"An arrangement in which copies of cryptographic keys are held by a trusted party so encrypted data can be recovered if keys are lost or legally required. Auditors assess escrow controls to balance recoverability against the risk of key compromise." },
  { term:"Non-repudiation", definition:"Assurance that a party cannot deny the authenticity or origin of a message or transaction, typically achieved through digital signatures and audit logs. It provides accountability and is essential evidence in disputes over electronic transactions." },
  { term:"Range Check", definition:"An input validation control that verifies a data value falls between a defined lower and upper boundary. Auditors test it to confirm that out-of-range entries, such as an invalid month or amount, are rejected at input." },
  { term:"Validity Check", definition:"An edit control that compares input data against a table of acceptable values to ensure only authorized codes are accepted. It prevents processing of transactions containing invalid or unauthorized entries." },
  { term:"Sequence Check", definition:"A control that verifies records or documents are in the expected numerical or chronological order and that none are missing or duplicated. Auditors rely on it to detect gaps that could indicate lost or unauthorized transactions." },
  { term:"Key Verification", definition:"A data entry control in which a second operator re-keys critical information and the system compares the two entries for agreement. Discrepancies signal keying errors before the data is accepted." },
  { term:"Echo Check", definition:"A data transmission control in which received data is returned to the sender to confirm it was transmitted accurately. It detects communication errors on point-to-point links between devices." },
  { term:"Parity Bit", definition:"A hardware-level error-detection control that appends a bit to data so the total number of set bits is consistently odd or even. A mismatch on receipt indicates a single-bit transmission or storage error." },
  { term:"Cyclic Redundancy Check (CRC)", definition:"A transmission control that computes a checksum over a block of data so the receiver can detect accidental changes. It is more robust than a parity bit for catching multi-bit errors in communications." },
  { term:"Materiality in IS Audit", definition:"The concept that an item is material if its omission or misstatement could influence decisions of report users, adapted for non-financial IT contexts such as system criticality and data sensitivity. It guides the auditor's scope, sample sizes, and reporting thresholds." },
  { term:"Audit Risk Model", definition:"The framework expressing overall audit risk as the product of inherent, control, and detection risk. Auditors use it to plan procedures so that, given assessed inherent and control risk, detection risk is set low enough to achieve acceptable overall assurance." },
  { term:"Compliance vs Substantive Testing", definition:"Compliance testing evaluates whether controls are operating as designed, while substantive testing verifies the accuracy and completeness of the data or transactions themselves. Results of compliance testing influence the extent of substantive procedures required." },
  { term:"Functional Acknowledgment", definition:"An electronic message in EDI confirming that a trading partner received and could interpret a transmitted transaction set. Auditors treat it as a control ensuring completeness and providing an audit trail for exchanged documents." },
  { term:"Atomic vs Aggregate Data", definition:"Atomic data is the lowest-level detailed transaction data, while aggregate data is summarized or rolled up for reporting. Auditors trace between the two to verify that summarized figures reconcile to underlying detail." },
  { term:"Regression Analysis (Analytical Procedure)", definition:"A statistical analytical technique that models the relationship between variables to form an expectation and identify unusual deviations. Auditors use it to develop precise expectations and flag figures that warrant further investigation." },
  { term:"Baseline Configuration", definition:"A documented, approved standard configuration for a system or device against which actual settings are compared. Auditors use baselines to detect unauthorized changes and to assess hardening compliance." },
  { term:"Recovery Point Consistency", definition:"The requirement that data restored from backups or replication represents a logically consistent state across related files and databases. Auditors verify that recovery does not leave interdependent records mismatched or partially updated." },
  { term:"Data Diddling", definition:"The unauthorized alteration of data before or during its entry into a system, often to conceal fraud. Auditors counter it with input validation, edit controls, and independent reconciliation of source documents to recorded data." },
  { term:"Piggybacking (Logical)", definition:"Gaining unauthorized system access by using another user's still-active authenticated session or credentials. Auditors mitigate it through session timeouts, re-authentication, and monitoring of concurrent logins." },
  { term:"Dual Control", definition:"A control requiring two authorized individuals to jointly complete a sensitive task, such as accessing keys or approving high-value transactions. It reduces the risk that a single person can commit or conceal an irregularity." },
  { term:"Screening Router", definition:"A router configured with access control lists to filter traffic based on source, destination, and port as a first line of network defense. Auditors assess its rule set to confirm that only authorized traffic is permitted." },
  { term:"Stateful Inspection Firewall", definition:"A firewall that tracks the state of active connections and makes filtering decisions based on the context of traffic flows rather than individual packets. It offers stronger control than static packet filtering by validating that packets belong to legitimate sessions." },
  { term:"Application-Level Gateway (Proxy)", definition:"A firewall that inspects and relays traffic at the application layer, understanding specific protocols and content. It provides granular control and logging but can introduce performance overhead compared to packet filters." },
  { term:"Demilitarized Zone (DMZ)", definition:"A screened subnet placed between internal and external networks to host publicly accessible services while isolating internal systems. Auditors verify that the DMZ architecture prevents direct external access to trusted internal resources." },
  { term:"Intrusion Detection vs Prevention", definition:"An intrusion detection system monitors and alerts on suspicious activity, while an intrusion prevention system can actively block or reject detected threats inline. Auditors assess tuning, coverage, and response processes for both." },
  { term:"Honeypot", definition:"A decoy system deliberately exposed to attract and study attackers away from production assets. Auditors and security teams use it to gather intelligence on attack techniques and to provide early warning of intrusion attempts." },
  { term:"Public Key Infrastructure (PKI)", definition:"The framework of hardware, software, policies, and certificate authorities that manages the creation, distribution, and revocation of digital certificates and keys. It underpins authentication, encryption, and non-repudiation for secure communications." },
  { term:"Certificate Authority (CA)", definition:"A trusted entity within PKI that issues and digitally signs certificates binding a public key to an identity. Auditors evaluate CA controls, key protection, and revocation processes because compromise undermines all issued certificates." },
  { term:"Certificate Revocation List (CRL)", definition:"A published list of certificates that have been revoked before their expiration and should no longer be trusted. Auditors verify that systems check revocation status so that compromised or invalidated certificates are rejected." },
  { term:"Digital Signature", definition:"A cryptographic value created with a signer's private key that verifies a message's authenticity and integrity and provides non-repudiation. Recipients validate it with the corresponding public key to confirm the message was not altered." },
  { term:"Symmetric vs Asymmetric Encryption", definition:"Symmetric encryption uses a single shared secret key for both encryption and decryption and is fast but complicates key distribution, while asymmetric encryption uses a public/private key pair enabling secure exchange and digital signatures. Many systems combine both, using asymmetric methods to exchange symmetric session keys." },
  { term:"Hashing vs Encryption", definition:"Hashing produces a fixed-length, one-way digest used to verify integrity and cannot be reversed to recover the original data, while encryption is reversible to protect confidentiality. Auditors confirm hashing is used for integrity checks and password storage rather than reversible protection." },
  { term:"Steganography", definition:"The practice of concealing data within other non-secret files such as images or audio so its very existence is hidden. Auditors and forensic examiners consider it a data exfiltration risk that evades content-based controls." },
  { term:"Single Sign-On (SSO)", definition:"An authentication arrangement that lets a user access multiple systems with one set of credentials. It improves usability and centralizes control but auditors note it concentrates risk, making strong authentication and session protection critical." },
  { term:"Kerberos", definition:"A network authentication protocol that uses tickets issued by a trusted key distribution center to verify identities without transmitting passwords over the network. Auditors assess time synchronization, ticket protection, and the security of the central authentication server." },
  { term:"Federated Identity Management", definition:"An arrangement that lets users authenticate in one domain and access resources in another trusted domain without separate credentials. Auditors evaluate trust agreements, token standards, and the controls each partner maintains." },
  { term:"Privileged Access Management (PAM)", definition:"Controls and tools that govern, monitor, and restrict the use of high-privilege accounts such as administrators. Auditors examine vaulting, session recording, and just-in-time access to confirm privileged activity is controlled and accountable." },
  { term:"Data Loss Prevention (DLP)", definition:"Technologies and policies that detect and block unauthorized movement of sensitive data across endpoints, networks, and storage. Auditors assess policy coverage and tuning to confirm that classified information is protected from exfiltration." },
  { term:"Change Advisory Board (CAB)", definition:"A group that evaluates, prioritizes, and authorizes significant changes to the IT environment. Auditors review its records to confirm that changes are properly assessed for risk, impact, and approval before implementation." },
  { term:"Emergency Change Procedure", definition:"An expedited process for implementing urgent changes needed to restore service, with retroactive documentation and approval. Auditors verify that emergency changes are logged, justified, and reviewed after the fact to prevent abuse of the fast-track path." },
  { term:"Version Control", definition:"The systematic management of changes to source code and documents, tracking revisions and enabling rollback. Auditors examine it to confirm that only authorized versions are promoted and that a reliable history exists for accountability." },
  { term:"Benefits Realization", definition:"The process of ensuring that a project or investment actually delivers the anticipated business value over time. Auditors assess governance mechanisms that track outcomes against the original business case." },
  { term:"IT Balanced Scorecard", definition:"A management tool that measures IT performance across financial, customer, internal process, and learning perspectives aligned to business goals. Auditors use it to evaluate whether IT contributes measurable value and aligns with strategy." },
  { term:"SOC 1 vs SOC 2 Reports", definition:"A SOC 1 report addresses controls at a service organization relevant to a user entity's financial reporting, while a SOC 2 report addresses controls relevant to security, availability, processing integrity, confidentiality, and privacy. Auditors rely on these third-party assurance reports when evaluating outsourced service providers." },
  { term:"Right-to-Audit Clause", definition:"A contractual provision permitting an organization or its auditors to examine a vendor's controls and records. Auditors confirm its inclusion so that assurance over outsourced processing can be independently obtained when needed." },
  { term:"Escrow of Source Code vs Data Escrow", definition:"Source code escrow protects the licensee's ability to maintain software if the vendor fails, while data escrow protects access to the organization's own data held by a provider. Auditors verify both where continuity of critical systems and information depends on a third party." },
  { term:"Recovery Testing", definition:"Exercises that validate an organization's ability to restore systems and operations within defined objectives after a disruption. Types range from checklist and walkthrough reviews to full interruption tests, each providing increasing assurance and risk." },
  { term:"Tabletop Exercise", definition:"A discussion-based continuity test in which participants walk through their roles and responses to a simulated scenario without activating systems. Auditors value it as a low-risk way to validate plan understanding and identify gaps before full testing." },
  { term:"Chain of Custody", definition:"The documented, unbroken record of who handled evidence and when, preserving its integrity for investigations or legal proceedings. Auditors and forensic examiners maintain it so that collected evidence remains admissible and reliable." },
  { term:"Write Blocker", definition:"A forensic hardware or software tool that permits reading data from a storage device while preventing any modification. It preserves the integrity of original evidence during forensic acquisition." },
  { term:"Log Correlation (SIEM)", definition:"The aggregation and analysis of log data from multiple sources by a security information and event management system to identify patterns indicating threats. Auditors assess coverage, retention, and alerting to confirm meaningful monitoring." },
  { term:"Time Synchronization (NTP)", definition:"Keeping clocks across systems aligned so that log timestamps are consistent and events can be reliably correlated. Auditors verify it because inaccurate time undermines the evidential value of logs and forensic reconstruction." }
];
GLOSSARY_CISA.sort((a, b) => a.term.localeCompare(b.term, undefined, { sensitivity: 'base' }));
